# TCP Chat Server (Go)

A simple multi-user TCP chat server written in Go, supporting global chat, private conversations, and chat rooms.

## Features

* Multi-client support using goroutines
* Persistent usernames (reconnect using the same name)
* Global chat
* Private messaging between users
* Chat room creation
* Add users to chat rooms
* Switch between conversations
* List joined chat rooms
* View current destination
* Built-in help command

---

## Requirements

* Go 1.20 or newer

---

## Running the Server

Clone the repository and start the server:

```bash
go run main.go
```

The server listens on:

```text
localhost:8080
```

You should see:

```text
Chat server running on port 8080
```

---

## Connecting to the Server

You can use any TCP client.

### Using Telnet

```bash
telnet localhost 8080
```

### Using Netcat

```bash
nc localhost 8080
```

When connected, enter your username when prompted:

```text
Enter your name:
```

Example:

```text
Alice
```

You will receive:

```text
Welcome Alice! Your ID is 1
Type /help to see available commands.
```

---

## Commands

### `/help`

Displays all available commands.

Example:

```text
/help
```

---

### `/to <username>`

Starts a private conversation with another user.

Example:

```text
/to Bob
```

All subsequent messages will be sent to Bob until the destination changes.

---

### `/tochat <chatname>`

Switches your destination to a chat room.

Example:

```text
/tochat Developers
```

---

### `/whereami`

Displays your current destination.

Examples:

```text
You are in the main chat
```

```text
You are chatting with Bob (ID: 2)
```

```text
You are in chat Developers (ID: 5)
```

---

### `/createChat <chatname>`

Creates a new chat room and automatically switches you to it.

Example:

```text
/createChat Developers
```

Response:

```text
Chat Developers created with ID 5
```

---

### `/addToChat <username> <chatname>`

Adds a user to an existing chat room.

Example:

```text
/addToChat Bob Developers
```

Response:

```text
User Bob added to chat Developers
```

The added user will receive:

```text
You have been added to chat Developers (ID: 5)
```

---

### `/listchats`

Lists all chat rooms you belong to.

Example:

```text
/listchats
```

Output:

```text
Chat: Developers (ID: 5)
Chat: Friends (ID: 7)
```

---

### `/changeTo <username|chatname>`

Changes your active destination.

Examples:

Switch to a user:

```text
/changeTo Bob
```

Switch to a chat room:

```text
/changeTo Developers
```

---

## Messaging

Sending a normal message sends it to your current destination.

Example:

```text
Hello everyone!
```

If no destination is selected, messages are sent to the global chat.

---

## Chat Behavior

### Global Chat

By default, users communicate through the main chat.

Example:

```text
[Alice]: Hello!
```

All connected users receive the message.

---

### Private Conversations

After:

```text
/to Bob
```

messages are delivered only to Bob.

---

### Chat Rooms

Users can create rooms and invite others.

Example workflow:

```text
/createChat Developers
/addToChat Bob Developers
/tochat Developers
```

All members of the room receive future messages sent there.

---

## Architecture

### Main Structures

#### User

Represents a connected user.

Fields include:

* ID
* Username
* Network connection
* Current destination
* Address

#### Chat

Represents a chat room.

Fields include:

* ID
* Name
* Members
* Message history

#### Message

Represents a message sent through the system.

Fields include:

* Destination chat ID
* Text content

---

## Concurrency

The server uses:

* Goroutines for handling multiple clients simultaneously.
* Mutexes to protect shared state.

Shared resources include:

* Connected users
* Existing chat rooms

---

## Example Session

User 1:

```text
Alice
/createChat Developers
/addToChat Bob Developers
Hello Bob!
```

User 2:

```text
Bob
/tochat Developers
Hi Alice!
```

Output:

```text
[Alice]: Hello Bob!
[Bob]: Hi Alice!
```

---

## Future Improvements

Possible enhancements include:

* Authentication and passwords
* Chat room ownership and permissions
* Message persistence using a database
* Offline message delivery
* Encrypted communication using TLS
* Administrative commands
* Better error handling
* User lists and presence indicators
* Migration from slice-based lookups to maps for improved performance

